      "\n\nWe have two ring isomorphisms:\n1. `g : S ≃+* T`\n2. `f : R ≃+* S`\n\nWe need to show that `g ∘ f : R →+* T` is also a ring isomorphism. The definition of `RingEquiv.comp` is given as:\n\n```tactics\ndef RingEquiv.comp (g : S ≃+* T) (f : R ≃+* S) : R ≃+* T where\n  toFun x := g (f x)\n  invFun x := f.symm (g.symm x)\n  left_inv := by\n    sorry\n  right_inv := by\n    sorry\n  map_add' := by\n    sorry\n```\n\nWe need to prove three things to show `g ∘ f` is a ring isomorphism:\n1. `left_inv`: For all `x : R`, `(g ∘ f) (f x) = x` (left inverse property)\n2. `right_inv`: For all `y : T`, `f (g y) = y` (right inverse property)\n3. `map_add'`: For all `x y : R`, `(g ∘ f) (x + y) = (g ∘ f) x + (g ∘ f) y` (addition preservation)\n\nLet's prove each of these.\n\n## Left Inverse Property\n\nWe need to show that for all `x : R`, `(g ∘ f) (f x) = x`.\nLet's compute `(g ∘ f) (f x)`. By definition, this is `g (f (f x))`.\nSince `f` is a ring isomorphism, `f` has an inverse `f.symm`. The property of an isomorphism is that `f (f.symm y) = y` for all `y : S` (right inverse property of `f`).\nSo, `f (f.symm (g (f x))) = g (f x)`.\nBut we need `g (f (f x)) = x`. Let's think.\n\nWait, perhaps we should use the left inverse property of `f`.\nThe left inverse property of `f` (given by `f.left_inv`) states that for all `y : S`, `f (f.symm y) = y`.\nSo, applying this to `g (f x)`, we get `f (f.symm (g (f x))) = g (f x)`.\nBut we need to get `x` from `g (f (f x))`.\n\nWait, perhaps we need to use the right inverse property of `g`.\nThe right inverse property of `g` (given by `g.right_inv`) states that for all `z : T`, `g.symm (g z) = z`.\nSo, applying this to `f x`, we get `g.symm (f x) = f x` is not right. We need `g (f x)`.\n\nWait, perhaps we need to apply `f`'s right inverse property.\n`f.right_inv` states that for all `z : S`, `f.symm (f z) = z`.\nSo, applying this to `x`, we get `f.symm (f x) = x`.\nNow, compute `g (f (f x))`. This is `g (f (f x))`.\nWe can rewrite `f (f